      section
        h1 The History of Empathy
      
      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        h1 SPOILER
        h2.headroom The term empathy is barely 100 years old
      
      section(data-bespoke-backdrop='romantic')
        h3 Romantic thinkers in the 18th century
        h2 such as Herder and Novalis
        h3 questioned their contemporary notion of Aesthetics
      
      section
        h2 Their main problem was that of expression.
        h3 If art and nature are incapable of experiencing human feelings.
        h4 How, then, can they express them?
      
      section
        h2 In 1872 Robert Vischer proposed an answer.
        h3 The explanation must lie in some unconscious process
        h3 of the person who views these forms.
      
      section
        h1 Einfühlung
        h3 Feeling Into

      section
        h2 The idea was first elaborated by Vischer
        h3 in "Das optische Formgefühl" (1872)
        h4 Aesthetic pleasure may thus be explained as objectified self-enjoyment in which subject and object are fused
        h4 Our ability to feel into art
      
      section
        h2 This was further explored by Theodor Lipps
        h3 "The Ästhetik" (1903-06)
        h4 He closely links our aesthetic perception and our perception of another embodied person as a minded creature.
        h4 The nature of aesthetic empathy is always the “experience of another human”
      
      section
        h2 In 1909
        h3 The term "Empathy" was introduced by psychologist
        h2 Edward Itchener
        h3 as a translation of the german term “Einfühlung”
      
      section(data-bespoke-backdrop='trippy-kitty-three')
        h1 Trippy Kitty Break
      
      section
        h1 The Neuroscience of Empathy
        
      section
        h3 Many of these ideas come from a fantastic talk by Jeremy Rifkin
        h3 THE EMPATHIC CIVILISATION
        :verbatim
          <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/l7AWnfFRc7g" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
      
      section(data-bespoke-backdrop='krang')
        h1 Healthy brains are wired for empathy
      
      section
        h3 One such phenomenon is a mirror neuron
        h4 the same neuron fires both when performing an action and when observing another doing the same action
        a.no-underline(href='https://www.thersa.org/discover/videos/rsa-animate/2010/05/rsa-animate---the-empathic-civilisation/')
          img(src='images/mirror.png' style='width:50%')
      
      section(data-bespoke-backdrop='giacomo')
        h3 This was first discovered by Italian scientists in the 1990's
        h4 Giacomo Rizzolatti, a neuroscientist at the University of Parma, noticed this strange phenomenon with a monkey and some peanuts.
      
      section(data-bespoke-backdrop='marco')
        h2 Marco Iacoboni,
        h4 Professor of Psychiatry and Biobehavioral Sciences, 
        h3 argued that mirror neurons are the neural basis 
        h2 of the human capacity for emotions such as empathy
      
      section(data-bespoke-backdrop='crybaby')
        h2 When a baby cries in a nursery
        h3 all the other babies join in
        h4 This is called Empathic Distress
        
      section(data-bespoke-backdrop='two')
        h2 Around two and a half years of age a child actually can begin to recognize themselves in the mirror
        h3 This increase in selfhood goes hand in hand with an increase in empathic development
        
      seciton(data-bespoke-backdrop='birth-and-death')
        h2 Around eight years of age a child learns about birth and death
        h3 They learn about Vulnerability
        
      section
        h2 Once you realize you have only one life, you can now feel others struggle
        h3 You know that they have their own lives, you know their struggle
      
      section(data-bespoke-backdrop='ouroboros')
        h3 Some philosophers, such as Schopenhauer, believe that empathic emotions such as compassion are possible because we are all parts of a greater ontological whole.
        
      section
        h3 It is important to remember
        h2 While our ability to FEEL empathy may be soft-wired
        h3 Our ability to act on it is a learnt trait

